<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec3-1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Introduction</title>
  <p>
    The <m>n^{\text{th}}</m> order linear differential equations are of the form
    <md xml:id="eq-nonhomogeneous-0" number="yes">
        a_n(x)y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = f(x)
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    where the functions
    <m>a_0(x), \dots, a_{n-1}(x), a_n(x)</m>
    and <m>f(x)</m> are continuous on some interval <m>I</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    We say that <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous-0"/> is
    <term>homogeneous</term> on <m>I</m> if <m>f(x)=0</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>,
    and <term>nonhomogeneous</term> on <m>I</m> if <m>f(x)\neq 0</m> for some <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>.
    We will typically have <m>a_n(x)\neq 0</m> on <m>I</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    If <m>a_n(x)=0</m> for some point in <m>I</m>, we restrict attention to a smaller interval,
    again denoted <m>I</m>, on which <m>a_n(x)\neq 0</m>.
    With this assumption, <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous-0"/> can be rewritten as
  <md xml:id="eq-nonhomogeneous0" number="yes">
      y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x)y' + a_0(x)y = f(x)
  </md>
</p>
  <p>
    This is achieved by dividing both sides of
    <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous-0"/> by <m>a_n(x)</m>, and redefining the coefficients.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-solutions">
    <title>Solution</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      A function <m>y=\phi(x)</m> defined on <m>I</m> is a
      <term>solution</term> of <xref ref="eq-nonhomogeneous0"/>
      if
    </p>
    
    </statement>
   
   
      <me>
        \phi^{(n)}(x) + a_{n-1}(x)\phi^{(n-1)}(x)
        + \cdots + a_0(x)\phi(x) = f(x)
      </me>
    
    <p>
      for all <m>x</m> in <m>I</m>.
    </p>
  </definition>

  <remark>
    <p>In <xref ref="def-solutions"/> we note the following considerations.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Derivatives at endpoints of <m>I</m> are understood as one-sided.
      </li>
      <li>
        Solutions may be complex-valued.
        If <m>\phi=\phi_1+i\phi_2</m>, then
          <m>\phi'=\phi_1'+i\phi_2'.</m>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </remark>


   <definition xml:id="IVP">
    <title>Initial Value Problem</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>a_0(x),\dots,a_{n-1}(x),f(x)</m> be continuous on <m>I</m>,
      <m>x_0\in I</m>, and <m>y_0,\dots,y_{n-1}</m> constants.
      The equation
    </p>
      <md>
        y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_0(x)y = f(x)
      </md>
    <p>
      together with
    </p>
      <md>
        y(x_0)=y_0,\;
        y'(x_0)=y_1,\dots,
        y^{(n-1)}(x_0)=y_{n-1}
      </md>
    <p>
      is called an <term>initial value problem (IVP)</term>.
    </p>
  </definition>

 <definition xml:id="BVP">
    <title>Boundary Value Problem</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>a_0(x),\dots,a_{n-1}(x),f(x)</m> be continuous on <m>I</m>,
      <m>x_0,x_1\in I</m>, and <m>y_0,y_1</m> constants.
      The equation
    </p>
      <md>
        y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_0(x)y = f(x)
      </md>
    <p>
      together with
    </p>
      <md>
        y(x_0)=y_0,\;
        y(x_1)=y_1
      </md>

    <p>
      is called a <term>boundary value problem (BVP)</term>.
    </p>
  </definition>
  

</section>
